The typical example for F corresponds to the balanced and bi-stable twin-pit F (u) = and  =  2. 1 (1 - u2 )2 , 4 -F (u) = u - u3

Equation (1.2) arises in the Gradient Theory of Phase Transitions [1]. In this physical model, there are two different states of a material represented by the values u = 1. It is of interest to study nontrivial configurations in which these two states try to coexist. Hence, the function u represents a smooth realization of the phase, which except for a narrow region, is expected to take values close to 1, namely the global minima of F . Let us consider the energy functional J (u) =
